e for each bin. So, perhaps the priority is higher for bins that can fit the item and have higher remaining space, or perhaps it's based on some heuristic like the first-fit, best-fit, or others.\n\nBut since the function needs to return a priority score regardless of whether the item can fit, perhaps the priority is a measure of how suitable each bin is for the item, even if it can't fit.\n\nAlternatively, the priority could be based on some measure that encourages the item to be placed in a bin that would minimize the loss, such as the difference between the bin's current size and the item's size.\n\nBut in the examples given, the functions don't seem to directly use the remaining space. Instead, they use functions like log, exp, sin, etc., combined with statistical measures of the bins.\n\nSo, perhaps the priority function is a heuristic that combines various factors, such as the bin's current size relative to the item, the bin's variability, mean, variance, etc.\n\nGiven that, I can think of different combinations:\n\n1. Multiply the item size with the bin's mean, then add a sine function based on the bin's standard deviation.\n\n2. Use the item size multiplied by the bin's variance, then add a cosine of the item over the bin's mean.\n\n3. Take the logarithm of the item plus one, multiply by an exponential of the item minus the bin's mean, then add a sine term involving the bin's standard deviation.\n\n4. Use the item size multiplied by the bin's standard deviation, then add a tangent of the item over the bin's variance.\n\n5. Combine the item with the bin's mean using an exponential, and add a cosine term involving the bin's variance.\n\n6. Use the item size multiplied by the bin's mean, then subtract the bin's standard deviation multiplied by a sine function of the item.\n\n7. Take the square root of the item plus the bin's mean, multiply by an exponential of the item minus the bin's variance.\n\n8. Use the item size multiplied by the bin's variance, then add 